{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos920.erdos_920 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos920.erdos_920.","id":"vf_5cd19cc022f9f980","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #920: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $g_k(n)$ denote the largest possible chromatic number of a graph with $n$ vertices which contains no $K_k$.\n\nIs it true that, for $k\\geq 4$,\\[g_k(n) \\gg \\frac{n^{1-\\frac{1}{k-1}}}{(\\log n)^c}\\]for some constant $c>0$? Current best: Shearer's lower bound for $R(3,m)$ (see [165]) improves this to\\[g_3(n) \\gg \\left(\\frac{n}{\\log n}\\right)^{1/2}.\\]The lower bound $R(4,m) \\gg m^3/(\\log m)^4$ of Mattheus and Verstraete \\cite{MaVe23} (see [166]) implies\\[g_4(n) \\gg \\frac{n^{2/3}}{(\\log n)^{4/3}}.\\]In general it is known (see [986]) that\\[R(k,m)\\gg (\\log m)^{-O_k(1)}m^{\\frac{k+1}{2}}\\]which implies\\[g_k(n) \\gg \\frac{n^{1-\\frac{2}{k+1}}}{(\\log n)^{c_k}}.\\]See [1013] for the case $k=3$. Prize: no. Tags: chromatic number, graph theory.","id":"vf_7c15851964bcf043","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/920.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_5cd19cc022f9f980","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:920","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_5cd19cc022f9f980","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_7c15851964bcf043","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source an